column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID
column168: It was reported that a driver has called the terminal to report the release. Unknown cause and unknown product leaking in the trailer (LE575). The trailer has 12 boxes (312 lbs) of Potassium Hydroxide (UN1814), 10 non reg material, 8 boxes (201 lbs) of Sulfuric Acid (UN2796). Unknown amount released and is contained to trailer at this time. Once the contractor arrives on site and verifies the product and amount released, any and all reporting requirements will be made.    ERTS has called the driver in an attempt to verify the released material and amount of the release. The driver (David Toland) reported that he entered the trailer to verify the leak. At this time he noticed that the leak was originating from a box labeled Blue Corral PH 11.00. The driver reported that his hands were covered in what was identified as sulfuric acid by his supervisor. ERTS has advised the driver that he needs to seek medical attention as a precautionary measure.     Contractor verified that the release was UN2796 Sulfuric Acid and that about 1 gallon was released to the trailer and asphalt. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident. It was reported that 2 pallets have been impacted and will be disposed of by the contractor. The contractor will re-palatalize the freight on these two pallets. The impacted freight will be removed from the boxes, neutralized, and placed in a salvage drum. The salvage drum will stay on the trailer and shipped on to the next terminal.The cardboard and any damaged freight will be marked as waste and disposed of by the contractor. Both the salvaged product and waste will be labeled as hazardous. The contractor will neutralize the trailer floor and the impacted ground.

column168: While offloading a trailer, the warehouse man discovered one palatalized box containing 13, 1 gallon bottles of 20% Sodium Hydroxide Solution which had leaked soaking a portion of the outer box. The box was enclosed in a clear poly bag. Facility personnel, under the supervision of a CleanPak specialist donned Level 3 PPE and proceeded to over-pack the plastic bottles into a 30 gallon poly drum using vermiculite as cushioning and absorbent. All PPE, the original outer box and the poly bag were placed in an additional 30 gallon poly drum. All material associated with this incident will be properly disposed of at an approved facility.
column169: All parties involved with this incident will be re-trained on the proper container selection, securement of contents and packaging requirements necesary for safe transportation. Conditions which may lead to a release or emergency response will be reviewed as well as appropriate steps to properly mitigate situations prior to them becoming incidents.

column168: Driver discovered the leaking trailer after stopping at the customer Security Gate 1 upon arrival at Solvay Chemical in LaPorte. Approximately 1-2 gallons of 98% Sulfuric acid was coming from the drain running from the top hatch around the dome lid and loading connections. The vent line valve was discovered to have been left open during transit. Notifications were made to the customer, supervisors and management. A team was dispatched to respond to the spill and clean up the scene. After neutralizing what was on the trailer and on the ground, the driver was allowed to enter the plant and complete his delivery. The cleanup was completed to the satisfaction of the customer and Supervisors checked the route of the truck to verify that no other incidents occurred between the supplier loading rack and the customer.
column169: Process Changes need to be updated at the Supplier level. At the current time after the loading process has taken place the driver is not allowed to ascend to the top of the trailer to verify ALL dome lids and valves are completely aligned and closed while on company property. Due to area constraints, and location of this supplier it is not Safety Friendly for the driver to pull out on the roadway and check his dome lid and valves for proper closer. This policy needs reviewing by both Univar and ECO Services.

column168: A mixed load of drums, pallets and totes had been loaded aat the Veolia Kent, WA facility and shipped to the Veolia Vancouver, WA in-transit facility to have additional materials added to the load before continuing on to Veolia in Henderson, CO. Upon inspecting the shipment approximately 30 minutes after the arrival of the truck, a leak was discovered to be coming from the back of the trailer.  Further investigation showed a leaking drum located toward the middle of the truck.  The drum was observed to have a horizontal crease approximately 4 inches long and located 4 inches from the bottom with a small hole at one edge of the crease which release about 20% of its contents.  Based on the location and description of the damage, and the knowledge that a tote was loaded immediately following, it was surmised that this drum must have been damaged by a forklift during loading of the tote into the trailer.  Confirmation measurements of the width of the tote and length of the forklift tines confirmed that the forklift tines were approximately 3-4" longer than the width of the tote.  The drum was over-packed into an 85 gal salvage drum with absorbent cushioning.  The spilled material was absorbed with floor dry.
column169: As this spill was caused by a forklift in the course of loading with the operator not realizing that the tines of the forklift had exceeded the tote he was moving and resulting in puncturing this drum, retraining and operator awareness will occur at both the Veolia Kent and Vancouver, WA locations.

column168: On May 02, 2016 at 15:30 hours personnel in the CSX Radnor Yard reported UTLX 206322, a loaded tank car of Alcohol, N.O.S., was suspected to have leaked from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Poet Ethanol Products, was notified via Professional Emergency Services. Joseph McCann, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, responded and found a faulty pressure relief valve.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Nick Hanna). The car was set out at Radnor Yard so the contents could be transloaded and the car cleaned/purged to allow safe movement to home shop for repair. A special switching move was required.  A QA 7.1 will be filed.     NARRI Severity Index:   2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32  NAR Tank Car Cause Code: 418

column168: At 1717 hours on May 11, 2016, a train crew working in the Kansas City Southern Beaumont Yard reported that railcar GATX 2089 was possibly leaking from the dome. The railcar, a Methyl Methacrylate Monomer load, was isolated for further investigation.  KCS Environmental & Hazmat dispatched an emergency response contractor to conduct air monitoring and investigate the railcar.       Responders reported that the leak originated from a loose packing gland on the liquid valve. The packing gland was tightened to stop the leak. Total amount released estimated at 3 gallons. All released material evaporated quickly.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: THIS WAS A DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TO A APARTMENT COMPLEX POOL HOUSE. THE DRIVER BACKED INTO THE UNLOADING POSITION IN THE PARKING LOT, PULLED HOSE OFF THE RACK TO THE CHEMICAL ROOM. THE DRIVER THEN ADDED AIR PRESSURE TO THE TANK, OPENED THE FLOW VALVES AND WENT INTO THE CHEMICAL ROOM TO CHECK PROGRESS. WHEN HE CAME OUT TO CHECK HIS AIR PRESSURE HE NOTICED A LEAK (PRODUCT) BY THE HOSE REAL. HE SHUT DOWN THE AIR COMPRESSOR TO BEGIN DROPPING AIR OFF THE BULK TANK. THE LEAK WAS NEAR THE PRODUCT VALVE SO HE WAS UNABLE TO SHUT THE LINE DOWN UNTIL THE PRESSURE DRAINED DOWN ENOUGH AS TO NOT INJURE HIMSELF. THE DRIVER WAS THEN ABLE TO SHUT DOWN ALL PRODUCT VALVES, TO CEASE THE FLOW OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE. HE SCALED OFF THE AREA TO PREVENT PUBLIC FROM BECOMING IN DANGER. A CALL WAS PUT INTO CHEMTREC AND THE MAIN OFFICE OF SLACK CHEMICAL TO INFORM OF THE PROBLEM. CONTAINMENT OF ANY RUN OFF WAS CONTAINED WITH SPILL PADS. A TOTAL AREA OF ABOUT 15'IN DIAMETER WAS AFFECTED WITH AN ESTIMATE 50 GALLONS LOST. PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION SHOWS A CRACKED THREADED PIPE TO BE THE PROBLEM. THE LEAK ITSELF BEFORE IT COULD BE SHUT DOWN WAS NO MORE THEN 5-6 MINS.
column169: WE ARE CURRENTLY HAVE A PLAN IN PLACE TO REPLACE AND /OR TEST ALL PIPING VALVES AND COUPLINGS ON THE MINI-BULK FLEET. THIS FAILURE PART IS BUILT INTO A HOSE REAL SYSTEM. IN THE FUTURE WE WILL BE INCLUDED A COMPLETE REPLACEMENT OF THIS PARTICULAR THREADED PIPE AS WELL.

column168: CBTX 728356 was reported leaking from the manway area at approximately 2135 hours on May 9, 2016. Ouray Environmental was dispatched to the scene to inspect, repair and remediate the leak.  Ouray personnel found that the gasket has worn and had a quarter inch separation and was worn.  They also found two manway bolts loose. Outage of the car was determined to be approximately 1.5 inches from the top of the manyway nozzle.  Ouray installed a shoulder style gasket and properly tightened all manway bolts to tool tight specs.  They placed a new seal, #20119, on the car and cleaned the product from the exterior tank.  The scene was cleared and the car was released at 00:45 hours on may 10.

column168: At 12:32 on 5/14/16, a report was received that GATX 8201, a loaded Spent Sulfuric Acid railcar, was leaking from the top of the tank car while being switched at the Kansas City Southern Railway Beaumont Yard. No injuries were reported.  GATX 8201 was isolated for further investigation and securement.      KCS Environmental + Hazmat Department dispatched an emergency response contractor to assess the railcar and affect proper securement. Upon investigation, the responder determined that the source of the leak was an open liquid line valve, and a loose liquid line valve secondary closure plug.  The valve and secondary closure plug were secured.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

Terminal personnel used kitty litter to clean the release. Terminal personnel placed the damaged pail and the impacted absorbents in a 55 gallon metal drum in OS & D.

It was reported that after the driver brought the product back to the terminal, personnel opened the door and found approximately 5 gallons of product from a 5 gallon pail on the trailer floor. A contractor was dispatched to clean up the spill.  The contractor cleaned the release with granular absorbents and place both the absorbents and debris into a 55-gallon steel waste drum.  Terminal personnel moved the trailer into the yard to allow it to air out.  The waste was placed into the terminal OS&D for future disposal. No other freight was damaged by the release and no drains, soils, or waterways were affected.

column168: DECISION TREE, APPROPIATE RESPONSE SHEET (FLAMMABLE LIQUID), FOLLOWED ACTION STEPS WASTE DISPOSAL DECONTAMINATION.

APPROACHED MY WORKSTATION SITUATED BETWEEN THE DAMAGE CAGE THE DESIGNATED HAZMAT DROP OFF AREA, WHERE I NOTICED THAT THE HAZMAT PACKAGES FROM AMERICAN MASTERTECH HAD ALREADY ARRIVED, THEY WERE SITTING ON A HAND TRUCK IN FRONT OF THE DESIGNATED HAZMAT DROP OFF AREA(SHELF). THEN I NOTICED THAT ALL OF THE HAZMAT PACKAGES ON THE AFOREMENTIONED HAND TRUCK HAD BEEN LEFT W/ THEIR ORIENTATION ARROWS POINTING SIDEWAYS. I IMMEDIATELY RECTIFIED THE PLACEMENT ERROR, REPOSITIONING THEM SO THE ARROWS POINTED UPWARDS. I RETURNED LATER AND DISCOVERED ONE OF THE PACKAGES WAS LEAKING, I NOTIFIED MGMT AND SINCE I'M AN ACCEPTANCE AUDITOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER, I DONNED APPROPRIATE PPE PLACED LEAKING PACKAGE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY. THEN I WENT BACK TO THE SMALL SORT, AS INSTRUCTED, AND FINISHED THE INCIDENT RESPONSE/DOCUMENTATION LATER ON IN THE SHIFT.
column169: THE ONLY PREVENTATIVE ACTIONS I CAN RECOMMEND WOULD BE THAT HAZMAT PACKAGES BE DROPPED OFF W/ THEIR ORIENTATION ARROWS POINTING UP, NOT SIDEWAYS. THE PACKAGES WERE POSITIONED ON THE HAND TRUCK SO THAT THEY WOULD BE IN AN UPRIGHT POSITION WHILE THE HAND TRUCK WAS UPRIGHT AND BEING USED, BUT THE HAND TRUCK WAS LEFT IN A "LYING DOWN POSITION" W/ THE PACKAGES, NO LONGER UPRIGHT, AND STILL ON IT.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON ITS SIDE. CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO SPILL FROM THE LIDS.
column169: LOADERS TO LOAD PACKAGES WITH ORIENTATIONS UP AND BLOCK IN HAZARDOUS PACKAGES TO PREVENT THEM FROM TIPPING OVER.

column168: On May 18, 2016, the drums were loaded onto a box trailer by the customer (BASF).  The drums were delivered to the Veolia Baytown 10-Day Facility the same day.  On May 23, 2016, Veolia employees inspected the drums prior to sending them back on the road to their final destination.  During this inspection, it was discovered that one of these drums had a 4-5 inch gash near the bottom of the drum with approximately 2 pounds of material on the floor near the drum.  The damaged drum was then over-packed into a salvage drum along with the material that had spilled out.  The drum was then sent to its final destination without further incident.
column169: It is believed the drum was damaged on the generator's site prior to being shipped. The generator of the drum was notified of the issue.  Also, the Veolia field crews were retrained on the importance of performing thorough inspections of all containers prior to shipping even when loaded by a customer.

column168: On May 5, 2016, a CTMV was found to have leaked approximately 2 gallons of product when it was pressurized for off-loading. The leak was the result of a small crack in the tank where a previous repair had been performed. The release was immediate and stopped once the tank was depressurized. As a precaution to avoid a release, the tanker was offloaded with a diaphragm pump. A contractor responded for cleanup and to perform the transfer. All generated waste was containerized and taken by the contractor for proper disposal. The CTMV has been sent to a vendor for repair.

column168: 5/21/2016: At 03:45, CR A. Richter, Risk Management, was contacted by TM R. Donahue, advising tank car BTRX 260002, load Petroleum Distillates, was found to have leaked from the top of the car, while a routine Mechanical inspection was being conducted on an outbound train at CR's Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ.    Further inspection by CR emergency response contractor, Hepaco, found three of six manway cover securement bolts were less than hand tight; and, the manway cover gasket was defective.    Gasket was replaced, cover closed, and all six manway cover securement bolts were made tool tight.  It was also noted the vapor valve securement plug was not even hand tight.  This was secured during Hepaco's inspection.    Car was wiped down after securement, and car was okayed for transportation.

column168: The driver picked up the container from the generator in Romulus, Michigan. The driver stopped in Burton, Michigan to re-manifest the load for delivery into Canada.As the driver inspected his vehicle and cargo he noticed liquid leaking from a crack in the right rear corner of the roll-off container body approximately one half way up from the bottom. The driver placed a bucket under the leak to catch the product and an absorbent sock around the bucket as a precautionary measure. The driver notified his supervisor who initiated an emergency response from a Clean harbors Field Service unit. The Field Service unit evaluated the situation upon arrival and developed a response plan taking into consideration all health and safety concerns. After donning appropriate PPE the Field Service Team transferred the product into an undamaged roll-off container along with all related clean up material and waste. The load was re-manifested and delivered to the Canadial disposal site without further incident.

column162: SVP HEALTH, SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: The incident captioned in this report occurred on 04/15/2016. The incident was not reported until 05/05/2016 due to a breakdown in the internal spill reporting protocol at the local level. This failure has been addressed and corrected. This shipment was fron a HHW pick-up and was exempt according to Washington State law. After picking up the material from its origin the driver noticed one of the drums had leaked a small amount of liquid onto the floor of his truck upon arriving at the next stop. The driver immediately cleaned up the spill and over packed the leaking drom at that site. After remediation the driver continued with his route but failed to report the incident to his superiors. These issues have been addressed as well. The material was subsequently disposed of at its original disposal destination without further incident.
column169: The delay in reporting is a result of misunderstanding and misconception regarding the spill reporting protocol. Thorough inspection of containers and pallets will be reinforced with drivers and warehouse personnel. Spill reporting protocol has been discussed and strongly reinforced with all parties to this incident.     Non-Hazardous Waste Manifest # 16015

column168: ON MAY 27, 2016 AT APPROX. 16:49, 2 HAZMAT PACKAGES WERE INSIDE A BOXLINE CAGE. BOTH HAD THE PROPERTIES OF CORROSIVE AND OXIDIZER. IT IS UNKNOWN WHAT CAUSED THE FIRE TO IGNITE, BUT AT ONE PACKAGE LEAKED. THE SUPERVISOR SAW VISIBLE SMOKE COMING FROM THE CAGE. HE CONTACTED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER AND PLANT ENGINEERING. THE SUPERVISOR STARTED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. THE PLANT ENGINEERING MECHANIC FINISHED EXTINGUISHING THE FIRE WITH THE SAME EXTINGUISHER. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER SECURED THE AREA, RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND PROCESSED THE DAMAGED PACKAGES THROUGH THE DAMAGE MATERIAL PROGRAM.

column168: BULK RETRIEVER ALERTED ME ABOUT A LEAKING HAZMAT ON BULK BELT; I DONNED MY PPE AND APPROACHED PACKAGE. I SAW THE CORROSION DIAMOND LABEL AND I PUT ON MY SILVER LINER GLOVES. NEXT, I FOLLOWED DECISION TREE, WHICH LED ME TO DISPOSAL. THEN I TOOK THE PACKING SLIP WITH INGREDIENT; IT WAS NITRIC ACID. TOOK FIVE INCHES OF PH TAPE AND IT MEASURED RED, AN ACID. I ADDED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE NITRIC ACID. ONCE NEUTRALIZED I PROCEEDED TO ADD ABSORBENT ACCORDING TO CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. I TOOK THE REST OF THE NITRIC ACID FOR DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

column168: During a yard inspection, an FRA inspector noted GATX 34713 was leaking product down the side of the tank car. Upon arrival, the responder noted the same. The responder climbed the car and noted liquid coming from the combination housing. The original seal was intact. The seal was cut and the housing cover opened. Product was noted as to be coming from a slightly opened liquid valve with a missing closure plug. The plug was noted as to be laying on top of the pressure plate next to the liquid valve. The valve was closed and the leak subsided. It was noted that the handle for the liquid valve was turned past parallel with the pressure plate and the stop tab slightly bent from too much force being utilized upon closure.   The handle was removed by the responder and the stop tab moved back to its original location. The liquid plug was cleaned, re-taped with Teflon tape, and tool tightened. After that was completed, the vapor valve plug was checked and was removed by hand. That plug was removed, cleaned, re-taped with Teflon tape, and tool tightened. Any remaining product evaporated from exterior of car.
column169: Shipper must reevaluate shipping procedures. This car had multiple failure points. Proper valve closing procedures as well as the proper installation of closure plugs must occur prior to shipping of any tank car to prevent the unnecessary release of hazardous materials in the future.

column168: ADMX 30445 was reported emanating vapors in the railyard on 5/4/2016.  After investigation the vapor source was at ADMX 30445's vacuum relief valve (VRV).  The faulty VRV was removed and a threaded pipe plug was secured in the vacated VRV orifice, which ended any further vapor release.  The VRV appeared to have a bent stem.
column169: Ensure the shippers pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: The BNSF 880173 was found with diesel fuel residue on the shell of the tank car while at Everett on 5/4/16.  The car was isolated and inspected by BNSF Hazmat responders.  Results of the inspection indicated that the leak originated from the manway sealing area between the nozzle and the manway lid.  The cause of the release was due a deteriorated gasket which no longer provided an adequate seal.  Less than 1 gallon of diesel fuel was spilled and was contained exclusively to the tank car body with no environmental impact.  The responder replaced the manway nozzle gasket, wiped the car down and re-secured the car for continuing on to destination.
column169: Follow up has been conducted with Energy Logistics.  The shipper should evaluate their tank car loading and securement procedures to see if there are any gaps in their ability to identify gasket condition and integrity.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: At 1232hrs the Manager of Yard Operations reported the car to be leaking from the bottom.  Local fire and police responded to secure the area.  Inspection of the car revealed a steady drip of product leaking from the bottom washout plate. A containment pool was placed to capture leaking product.  Tightening of four nuts which secured the washout plate approximately one half turn each slowed the release, but did not stop it. Remaining residue product in car was recovered with a vacuum truck.  Upon removal of all product, car was set out for further handling by the leaser of the car.  On 6-2-15, Rescar mobile rail repair removed the washout cover plate, and determined the gasket was too small in diameter.  Additionally, the internal washout plug was loose, not wrench tight. An appropriately sized gasket was positioned on the washout cover plate and then secured to the car.  The shipper will apply for an OTMA and car will be home shopped for further inspection and repairs.  It should be noted that the car was on its first trip after being shopped for liner inspection and repainting.  Magnetic tape was also noted covering the commodity name on left and rights sides of the car, and has been been removed.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column168: Honeywell was transporting a loaded cargo tank when the driver observed smoke coming from the trailer.  He pulled off the roadway, exited the cab and observed flames coming from the rear brake area.  He called 911 for assistance.  The local fire department responded to extinguish the fire.  The rear tires were destroyed or damaged severely by the fire.  The brakes were the source of the fire and also considered inoperable.  There was no noted structural damage to the lading retention system or detectable damage requiring repair to a lading retention system.  At no point was there a release of hazardous material.  The cargo tank was transferred to a trailer and hauled back to the shipper for offloading, repair and retesting.
column169: There was no release of hazardous material or failure of the packaging.  The root cause of the brake fire is under investigation.

column168: A 55 gallon steel drum of UN1263 Gold Enamel arrived at the R&L Carriers terminal in Farmington, MN punctured and leaking.  It was apparent that the drum had been punctured by other freight during transit. The damaged drum released approximately 2 gallons of product to the trailer floor.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release. The damaged drum was over-packed, labeled as salvage and staged on site for R&L to manage.

Approximately 1 quart of UN3262 Barium Hydroxide Monohydrate released from a 2100 lb. plastic IBC (super sack) due to an apparent forklift puncture on the bottom of the container. The release impacted the trailer floor and was confined to the inside of the trailer. A contractor responded and transferred the product from the damaged container into 55 gallon poly drums. All waste and cleanup debris was containerized for disposal.

The employee stated that he was moving a tank from one spot to another with a fork lift. The employee did not secure the tank with a chain and when he moved it the tank rolled off the fork lift and hit the vapor valve and tore it off resulting in 50 gallons of propane be released into the air. There were no injuries and no other property damage.
column169: Conduct safety meeting on the fork lift and enforce the proper procedures on securing items that are being moved before moving them.

column168: Approximately 1 pint of UN3264 "Sure Klean Residential BricKLEAN" released from (2) 5 gallon plastic jerricans that were crushed between the forklift and the wall of the trailer during offloading activities. column168: Driver was parked taking a break. At 08:00 driver was doing a walk around pre-trip and noticed that there was a drip at the front of the tanker over the rear tandems of the truck. Upon discovering the drip, appropriate personal and authorities were notified. Fire department and police department were dispatched to the scene. LA State police hazmat and LA DEQ were notified. USES Environmental was dispatched to the scene to transfer load into another tanker and clean up spill. Small spill was contained on a concrete surface. USES arrived on scene at 09:50 and transfer of load was complete at 13:37. Decon and cleanup was completed at 14:41.
column169: Continue focused training on tanker inspection techniques with an emphasis on inspecting welds for cracks.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While traveling, tank rollover resulted in the loss of approximately 2 gallons of diesel fuel, 3 gallons of motor oil, and 10 gallons of ethanol. Local FD and State Police responded to assess the site. Indiana Spill Response (ISR) was contracted to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival onsite, tanker was in tact with product only releasing from the vapor recovery tube on tanker. Saddle tanks were also intact, with release from fuel cap while vehicle was on its side, and motor oil releasing from the engine. Erwin Bros Trucking dispatched a recovery tanker to offload tanker. ISR dyked the area, as a precautionary measure, to prevent migration. Upon completion of offload and recovery of vehicle, ISR excavated the impacted soil beneath the vehicle.Area was scraped per visual and olfactory observation. IDEM representative oversaw cleanup and was satisfied with response efforts. No further action was required. Waste was transported off site, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were on injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Erwin Bros Trucking will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column62: Broken Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Product was reported to be leaking from the bottom of the car.  Inspection revealed the bottom outlet valve cap to be loose 1 turn.  Additionally, the welded seal rod bracket which secures the valve operating handle in the closed position was broken, and not attached to the bottom of the car.  This failure caused the valve to vibrate open allowing product to leak. The bottom outlet ball valve was closed, and the cap was tightened 1 turn which secured the car from further release.  The shipper dispatched Rescar to remove the valve operating handle so it would not vibrate open.  Car was then released and placed back into transportation.  Upon off loading, the car will be shopped for necessary repairs.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column168: On 17 May 2016 the CSX PSCC was alerted by the Brooklyn Junction Yard Trainmaster in New Martinsville that tank car GATX 214077 was discovered with an audible noise from the protective housing that was discovered at ground level. The Train-master isolated the area. CSX Manager Hazardous Materials Joseph Taylor was notified and contracted Specialized Professional Services, Inc of Washington, PA to respond.     Upon arrival of SPSI, it was confirmed the car had an audible release, no liquid or vapor was visible to the eye. When ascending the car, the protective housing was accessed. SPSI discovered that both A End and B End liquid line operating valve handles were partially open. The vapor line operating valve handle was partially open. All 3 secondary closure plugs were found less than hand tight.     The release was terminated by closing all valves and installing all secondary closure plugs to tool tightness. All reporting requirements were met, no injuries incurred, and no delay in transportation traffic was experienced.

column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING 93% SULFURIC ACID DURING A FIST DELIVERY TO KIA IN WEST POINT, GA. AFTER THE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED, IT WAS NOTICED THAT LIQUID WAS LEAKING BELOW AND AROUND THE PUMP BOX. THERE WERE NO OBVIOUS LEAKS IN ANY OF THE DELIVERY PIPING, PUMP, OR HOSES. THERE WAS A 6' BY 3'AREA BENEATH THE TRAILER THAT WAS WET WITH LIQUID. A PH CHECK DETERMINED IT WAS SULFURIC ACID AND THE ACID SEEMED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BARREL OF THE TRAILER. HEPACO WAS CALLED IN TO NEUTRALIZE AND REMEDIATE THE AFFECTED AREA. TWO PAILS OF NEUTRALIZED WASTE (5 GALLONS EACH) WERE GENERATED.     THE TRAILER HAD BEEN IN FOR AN HM 183 IN FEBRUARY 2016. NO DEFECTS WE DETECTED AT THAT TIME. UPON INSPECTION AFTER THE INCIDENT, A PIT WAS NOTICED IN A WELD ON A BAFFLE AND IS BELIEVED TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.
column169: REVIEW OF EQUIPMENT AGES AND TOLERANCE FOR RISK FROM OLDER EQUIPMENT. IMPLEMENTATION OF PM PROGRAM. ADDITION OF TWO NEW TRAILERS. REVIEW PROCEDURES FOR CHECKING TRAILER AREA DURING DELIVERY.

The employee was evacuating residential tanks on the lot into a company bulk truck. When he removed the truck hose the space between the two valves had pressured up again with liquid propane, when he disconnected the truck hose this released approximately 1 gallon of liquid propane, hitting the employee on his right side resulting in a first degree chemical burn to his abdomen, right arm, and  left arm. He was given ibuprofen, Acetaminophen/Codine. The area is swollen and blistered the area was irrigated with sterile saline and applied silvadene and loose dressing. No lost time from work the employee is working regular duty work.

column168: THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER WAS PICKED UP AT THE PORT OF CHARLESTON, SC. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DELIVER SITE THE CONSIGNEE NOTICED PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER. UPON EXAMINATION, ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS FOUND TO BE PUNCTURED BY THE TIP OF A FORKLIFT FORK. THE PUNCTURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 3 TO 4 INCHES WIDE AND APPROXIMATELY 1 INCH IN HEIGHT. THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED NEAR THE FIRST RING FROM THE TOP. THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS REFUSED AND TAKEN TO A FACILITY TO BE UNLOADED, THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE RESIDUE REMOVED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE LEAK WAS CONFINED TO THE FREIGHT CONTAINER FLOOR. THE LEAKED PRODUCT HAD SOLIDIFIED INTO A SOLID GLUE-LIKE SUBSTANCE.
column169: THE SHIPPER SHOULD INCLUDE IN THEIR FORK LIFT TRAINING FOR THE OPERATOR NOT TO EXTEND THE FORKS PAST THE OTHER SIDE OF THE PALLET BEING LIFTED TO PREVENT THE FORK FROM DAMAGING ANY OF THE FREIGHT. INCLUDE VISUAL VERIFICATION BY THE FORK LIFT OPERATOR BEFORE SETTING THE PALLET TIGHT UP AGAINST OTHER FREIGHT.

UNDECLARED PACKAGE DISCOVERED LEAKING IN UPS FACILITY.

Upon inspection by an FRA inspector, product was noticed leaking from the protective housing of the car. BNSF responder inspected the car and found the liquid valve to be loose at the base. The bolts at the base of the valve were tightened and appeared to fix the leak. A hazmat contractor was called to do a bubble test on the car to be sure the fittings were tight and not leaking. Once the vacuum relief valve was tightened, the car passed the bubble test. The released product was cleaned off the car and the car was released to destination. No product reached the ground.
column169: The shipper should make sure to reinforce through training the importance of securing all appliances on the rail car prior to loading and releasing the car. The use of a pressure test prior to or after loading can also provide positive confirmation of a secure package prior to shipment.

The release was a UN 3264 "water treatment chemical" at the PVR terminal; 275 Pine St. Seekonk, MA 2771. It was reported that at least one 55 gallon poly drum was damaged during transit. When the driver made it to the terminal, he noticed that there was a slow dripping from the nose of the trailer. Approximately 2 gallons has released to the ground below the nose of the trailer. The contractor, Clean Harbors, responded, cleaned the 20-30 gallons of released material and produced (1) 95 gallon poly drum containing the damaged drum, and (2) 55 gallon poly drums of impacted clean up debris.

The train crew noticed an odor coming from PROX 24056 while in the yard in Lafayette, LA. The mechanical supervisor noted liquid visible coming down the side of the car which quickly evaporated. A hazmat contractor was dispatched to the car to investigate and found all fittings secure no leaks. The train crew moved the car to check for leaks and a small leak was discovered from the manway of PROX 24056. Upon opening the manway, it was observed that the manway gasket was misaligned and not fully engaged on the manway nozzle resulting in a leak.    The gasket was re-aligned, the tank car was secured and moved again to check and no longer leaked. The car was released to destination.
column169: The loading and pre-check personnel should review their training and procedures to prevent this from occurring in the future. The pre-check is especially important when receiving a rail car from the shop for its first load.

Shipper tendered a shipment of tools and stated that the shipment did not contain any hazardous materials. During the screening process screener discovered that the shipment contained electric drills with multiple batteries. The shipment was not marked with a lithium battery label. The batteries were tendered loosely in a soft sided tool bag. The batteries were also not contained in any type of inner packaging nor were the terminals protected from accidental activation. Local FAA office was informed and came to inspect the shipment.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: At 05:00 on 5/25/2016, the BOCX 3041 car was found during a camera yard check to be abnormally venting argon gas from the vent line.  Mechanical Hazmat crews responded to inspect the car and found it to be venting normally at the time of inspection.  In reviewing the camera footage, it was noted that the venting was not normal.  The cabinets were opened to obtain car pressure.  Current pressure was at 57 psi, the Safety Relief Valve (SRV) is designed to open at 60 psi.  It was determined in consultation with Linde personnel that the SRV was activating due to high internal pressures.  The car was isolated and on 5/26/16, Linde personnel vented the car to bring pressures down to 15 psi.  Another release through the SRV was not reported from the time of the inspection on 5/25/16 and when the car's pressure was lowered.  The car was then released for continued transportation to destination.
column169: The shipper was advised of the circumstances and situation and asked to determine the cause of the overpressure to ensure that a similar situation does not happen again.

column168: WHILE LOADING A SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE AT THE CUSTOMER'S SITE, A POLY DRUM WAS NOT SECURED PROPERLY ON THE DRUM DOLLY, CAUSING THE DOLLY TO PUT A SMALL PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE EMPLOYEE WAS ALREADY WEARING THE PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT SO HE IMMEDIATELY BEGAN TO PUT DOWN ABSORBENT PADS AND OVERPACK THE DRUM INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE CONTAINER. THE MATERIAL USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ALSO PLACED INTO THE DRUM. THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE WERE NOTIFIED - INCIDENT NUMBER 16-01911. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN LOADED ON A TRUCK TO THE INTERMEDIATE TRUCK TRANSFER FACILITY WHERE IT THEN LATER WENT TO THE INTENDED WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-INSTRUMENTS OR ARTICLES
column168: On May 25, 2016, a Pacific Northwest National Laboratory (PNNL) staff member prepared a Pelican case containing a home smoke detector, 13 thorium welding electrodes and 6 lantern mantles, and transported the case from Richland, WA to his home in Kennewick, WA, a highway distance of ~20 miles.  On May 31, 2016, PNNL's Hazardous Material Transportation Officer (HMTO) became aware of the transport and recognized it met the definition of undeclared hazardous material.  The HMTO reported the error to the PNNL Operations Center, which initiated communications to others responsible to evaluate compliance, reporting and corrective actions.  Although the Pelican case met excepted packaging criteria, it lacked the required UN2911 marking.  In addition, the staff member who had prepared and transported the package lacked the required DOT training.  There was no package failure and no release.  The HMTO went to the staff member's home, prepared a compliant package, and returned the regulated items to PNNL.
column169: Existing PNNL procedures require that staff identify all materials (hazardous or not) to be shipped and obtain services of qualified staff to prepare/ship hazmat, and that staff who participate in hazmat operations receive hazmat employee training.  If the staff are unsure whether hazards are present, they must contact a hazmat shipper for review.  PNNL's orientation and annual refresher for all staff include information about the regulated nature of hazardous materials in transportation and the need for hazmat employee training for certain operations.  PNNL also regularly publishes communications to all staff to raise awareness of hidden hazards in transportation.  Both the trainings and the regular communications specifically identify smoke detectors, lithium batteries and other common commercial commodities that are DOT regulated when shipped in commerce.  Regardless, it did not register with the staff member that the contents were regulated.    In accordance with Department of Energy requirements, PNNL has initiated a critique, an extent-of-condition review, and a causal analysis to identify contributing factors and means to prevent recurrence.  This process is not yet complete.  The staff member has since completed general awareness, safety and security awareness training, and is scheduled to complete function-specific training.  Management has reinforced requirements to other project staff.    Because the public may lack an understanding of hazardous materials and requirements associated with consumer commodities, there may be a misperception that there are no special requirements when shipping those materials by US Postal Service or commercial carriers, or when otherwise transported in commerce.  Including more detailed information regarding the presence of hazards and the limits of transport on packagings might help raise awareness.

column168: THE PORTABLE DOCK PLATE AT THE OFFERER LOCATION COULD NOT BE USED IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING THE DRUMS ONTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. THE DOCK PLATE OVERLAPPED APPROXIMATELY 12 INCHES OF THE FLOOR SPACE NOT LEAVING ENOUGH SPACE TO PLACE THE 4 X 55 GALLON DRUMS ON THE BACK OF THE TRAILER WITHOUT RESTING THEM ON THE DOCK PLATE. THE DRUM WAS LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER USING THE DRUM CART. THE TRANSITION ONTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER CAUSED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM TO SLIDE OFF THE BASE OF THE DRUM DOLLY. THE WEIGHT OF THE DRUM RESTING ON THE PRONGS OF THE DRUM DOLLY CAUSED A SMALL PUNCTURE AT THE BASE OF THE DRUM. THE PUNCTURE WAS ABOUT 1/4" X 3" AND WAS LOCATED ABOUT 4" FROM THE BASE OF THE DRUM. THE DRUM LEAKED FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 SECONDS PRIOR TO IT BEING LAID DOWN ON ITS SIDE WITH THE HOLE FACING UP TO STOP THE DRUM FROM LEAKING FURTHER. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF THE DRUM AND ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND IN BETWEEN THE LOADING DOCK AND THE TRAILER ONTO THE ENCLOSED CONCRETE LOADING DOCK AREA. WITHIN 10 MINUTES THE CONTENTS OF THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WERE TRANSFERRED INTO A NEW CONTAINER. ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE USED TO CLEANUP THE SPILLED MATERIAL ON THE CONCRETE LOADING DOCK, INSIDE THE TRAILER, AND AT THE CONCRETE PAD AT THE BASED OF THE COVERED INDOOR LOADING DOCK. THE USED ABSORBENT WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN AN APPROPRIATE CONTAINER.
column169: REVIEW LOADING PROCEDURES WITH FIELD PERSONNEL, ENSURE A DOCK PLATE IS ALWAYS BEING UTILIZED WHEN LOADING/UNLOADING TRAILERS.

column168: At approximately 06:35 on 05/30/16, LARS informed by hub personnel that unit arrived destination leaking a substance from the middle of the trailer.  ERTS was contacted at 07:00 and dispatched Patriot Environmental to remediate leaking condition. Contractor arrived on site at 11:00.  Interior inspection revealed mixed freight loaded in two rows with a second layer throughout. Some second layer pallets were resting on ETrack bars  while others were resting directly onto base units. No load securement was observed anywhere within this shipment.  Contractor identified the cause of the leaking condition to be a pallet of batteries approximately 1/3 back from the nose of the trailer on the right side that  slid off of base unit and came to rest on its side. All batteries on the pallet remained in place but were lying horizontal, allowing acid to leak. Acid leaked  onto and through the floor of the trailer.  Contractor unloaded and cleaned cargo pallets, cleaned trailer, then reloaded cargo. Contractor also cleaned affected ground area. Hazmat waste from  this incident was removed by Patriot Environmental. Job was completed and contractor departed at 18:00.    The packaging consisted of lead acid batteries that had been banded to a wooden pallet and shrink wrapped.
column169: Shipper provided information to address improper loading conditions which led to the release.  Follow up should be performed by YRC to prevent future incidents.

column168: CN Transportation Department employee noted a leak from the bottom outlet of tank car PLCX 224473 (Residue: UN3256, ELEVATED TEMPERATURE L IQUID,FLAMMABLE, N.O.S. BENZOAPYRENE, DIBENZAHANT CLASS 3 / PG III) at the CN President's Island Yard, Memphis TN. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting a brown liquid dripping from the bottom outlet valve. The top operated, bottom outlet valve was not closed completely and the packing nut required 2 1/2 turns to seal. The bottom outlet cap was also found to be less than tool tight allowing product to escape. Tank car was released for further movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A Norfolk Southern train derailed 13 cars in South Whitley, IN.  The derailment involved 3 tank cars containing hazardous materials.  The derailment resulted in no release of hazardous material.  Local first responders evacuated 6 houses as a precaution.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: DRIVER (JOSE REYES) OF SOCO FUEL TRUCK TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 8 WAS EXITING ONTO THE MORENA BLVD. EXIT AT 6PM, WHICH IS POSTED AT 45MPH FOR APPROXIMATELY 50-75 YARDS AND  A SECOND POSTED SPEED LIMIT SIGN IS 20MPH AT A RIGHT CURVE ON THE TRANSITION TO MORENA BLVD. DRIVER (JOSE REYES) STATED HE WAS TRAVELING AT 30MPH WHEN ENTERING CURVE SECTION OF THE EXIT RAMP. HE REMEMBERS TILTING TO THE LEFT AT THAT POINT TRYING TO STOP THE TRUCK WITH THE BRAKES BUT WAS TOO LATE AND THE VEHICLE ROLLED ONTO THE LEFT SIDE AND SKIDDED FOR APPROXIMATELY 45 FEET, RIPPING THREE HOLES ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE FUEL TANK AT COMPARTMENTS 1, 2, & 3.     DRIVER SUSTAINED A MINOR INJURY AND WAS ABLE TO NOTIFY COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE ABOUT THE ACCIDENT. FIRST RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED ALONG WITH THE COMPANIES OSROW. SEVERAL COMPANY PERSONNEL WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN THE HOUR AND BEGAN THE NOTIFICATION TO ALL THE NECESSARY AGENCIES. NRC DEPLOYED BOOMS IN THE RIVER ALONG THE STORM DRAINS. THEY BEGAN REMEDIATION OF THE CONTAMINATED AREAS THROUGHOUT THE NIGHT AND FOR THE NEXT COUPLE OF WEEKS.
column169: THE SOCO GROUP PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON CARGO TANK DRIVER ROLLOVER PREVENTION PROVIDED BY (US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION) WAS HELD AT EACH TERMINAL THE FOLLOWING WEEK.

column168: DRIVER LOADED FUEL AT TERMINAL IN SELMA AND WAS EN ROUTE TO CUSTOMER LOCATION IN WAKE FOREST. THE DRIVER DOES NOT RECALL ANY DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT. IT IS BELIEVED THAT HE WAS DISTRACTED FROM DRIVING AND WENT OFF THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND OVER-CORRECTED, CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO OVERTURN. POLICE EMS AND OUR DISPATCH WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED. WE CALLED EASTERN ENVIRONMENTAL TO CONTAIN THE SPILL OF FUEL.
column169: ADDITIONAL DISTRACTED DRIVING TRAINING HAS BEEN GIVEN.

column169: PRIOR LOADING TERMINAL MANAGEMENT SHOULD USE THIS INCIDENT AS A RETRAINING TOOL WITH FREIGHT LOADERS.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER. ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE RELEASE WAS PROPERLY MANAGED. THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: ALWAYS SECURE FREIGHT TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.

column168: DRIVER WAS SITTING INSIDE THE CAB OF HIS TRUCK COMPLETING PAPERWORK, WHILE PUMP WAS RUNNING (THIS IS AGAINST COMPANY POLICY). TANKER OVERFLOWED CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 50 GALS OF CRUDE OIL TO GO ON TO THE CONCRETE DRIVEWAY. ALPHA PETROLEUM DISPATCHED OUR OWN ER CREW, IN ORDER TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL. DIKES/BERMS WERE IMMEDIATELY PUT IN PLACE, IN ORDER TO CONTAIN SPILL. ALPHA PROCEEDED TO THOROUGHLY CLEAN THE AREA WITH ABSORBENT, PRESSURE WASHERS. WASTE WAS DRUMMED, LABELED AND TRANSPORTED FOR DISPOSAL AT YUMA ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, EPA ID# AZR000515924.
column169: ALL ALPHA DRIVERS HAVE BEEN COUNSELED AND RETRAINED, AS IT RELATES TO LOADING AND UNLOADING OF BULK LIQUID LOADS. ALL DRIVERS ARE TO STAY IN IMMEDIATE LOADING/UNLOADING AREA AND NOT ALLOWED, IN CAB OF TRUCKS WHILE LOADING/UNLOADING IS TAKING PLACE.     THIS DRIVER WAS TERMINATED FOR THIS SPECIFIC INCIDENT.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: -3 RAILCARS SPOTTED AT UNLOADING STATIONS TO BE OFFLOADED.     -OPERATOR FAILED TO PROPER SECURE THE OFFLOADING HOSE CONNECTION TO ONE OF THE 3 RAILCARS.     -RAILCARS WERE PRESSURIZED WITH AIR TO START THE OFFLOADING PROCESS.     -THE RAILCAR THAT THE OFFLOADING HOSE WAS NOT SECURELY FASTENED TO BEGAN TO LEAK SULFURIC ACID FROM THE TOP CONNECTION POINT OF THE RAILCAR.     -THE SAFETY OBSERVER QUICKLY NOTICED THE LEAKAGE ACTIVATED.     -THE REMOTE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF SWITCH WHICH STOPS THE FLOW OF AIR TO THE RAILCAR    -DURATION OF THE LEAK = ABOUT 5 MINUTES.     -NEUTRALIZING AGENT APPLIED TO AFFECTED AREAS THE CLEANED UP.
column169: -FIRST COURSE OF ACTION WAS A SAFETY STAND WITH OPERATORS- INCIDENT REVIEW AND REVIEW OF STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE.     -SECONDLY, WE ARE INSTALLING AN INTERLOCK SYSTEM THAT WILL REQUIRE A SECOND OPERATOR TO VISUALLY INSPECT THAT ALL CONNECTIONS HAVE BEEN MADE. ONCE SATISFIED, THIS SECOND PARTY "INSPECTOR" WILL ACTIVATE A CONTROL PANEL THAT WILL THEN ALLOW THE UNLOADING PROCESS TO CONTINUE.

column14: NORTH SERVICE RD OF US HWY 80
column168: ON MAY 26TH THE ARNOLD TRANSPORTATION SERVICES TRUCK WAS TRAVELING WEST ON US HWY 80. APPROXIMATELY 04:35 THE DRIVER SUFFERED FROM A MEDICAL EMERGENCY THAT RENDERED HIM INCAPACITATED. DUE TO THIS, THE TRUCK VEERED OFF US HWY 80 ON TO THE NORTH SERVICE ROAD RAMP AND THEN OVERTURNED. THE TRUCK FINALLY RESTED PARTIALLY ON THE SERVICE ROAD AND PARTIALLY ON THE SHOULDER. THERE WAS A DRAINAGE DITCH JUST OFF THE SHOULDER. THE TRUCK WAS HAULING 12 TOTES OF ADOX 3125, A SODIUM CHLORITE SOLUTION AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT. WHEN THE TRUCK OVERTURNED, THE TOTES WERE FLIPPED WITHIN THE TRUCK AND FOUR OF THE CONTAINERS SUSTAINED DAMAGE AND LEAKED. AN ESTIMATED 500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WITHIN THE TRUCK AND FOUR OF THE CONTAINERS SUSTAINED DAMAGE AND LEAKED. AN ESTIMATED 500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE TRUCK AND IN THE DRAINAGE DITCH. THE DRAINAGE DITCH DID HAVE WATER PRESENT FROM A PREVIOUS RAIN EVENT. AS THE CHLORITE SOLUTION CAME IN TO CONTACT WITH THE STANDING WATER SOME VAPORS WERE RELEASED. WHEN EMERGENCY SERVICES ARRIVED THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL. MR. STEVE HOWIE, KAUFMAN COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT, CONTACTED THE CLEANING GUYS LLC TO CONDUCT THE CLEANUP OF THE RELEASED CHEMICAL. MR. HOWIE BEGAN AN EVACUATION OF SURROUNDING BUSINESSES AND SHUT DOWN US HWY 80 WHILE THE CLEANUP TOOK PLACE.     THE RESPONSE COMPANY BROUGHT IN A TANK TRUCK AND PUMPED OFF ALL THE PRODUCT AND WATER FROM THE DRAINAGE DITCH AND ALL REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE DAMAGED TOTES. THE TOTES WERE ALL IN A CONDITION THAT COULD NOT BE SHIPPED. IT WAS UNCLEAR IF THE FOUR LEAKING TOTES WERE DAMAGED AT THE SEAMS OR IF THEY WERE PUNCTURED BY THE METAL FRAME OF THE TRAILER ROOF. THE CLEANING GUYS LLC PREPARED AND SUBMITTED A REPORT TO THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY REGARDING THE FINAL CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL OF THE ADOX 3125 PRODUCT. THERE IS A COPY OF THE BOL AND SOME PICTURES ATTACHED.

column168: DRIVER ERROR, TRAVIS JONES ROLLED TRUCK AND TRAILER ON A CURVE CAUSING THE RELEASE OF 7926 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. THE GASOLINE HAD RUN ACROSS THE HIGHWAY INTO A BAR DITCH AND CONTINUED SOUTH FOR HUNDREDS OF FEET BEFORE HITTING A CULVERT CROSSING THE ROAD AND RAN ANOTHER 173 FEE INTO A RUNOFF AREA, WITH THE ADOT ROW AND SAN CARLOS APACHE INDIAN RESERVATION. TRAVIS JONES WAS AIRLIFTED TO HOSPITAL. 40 TONS OF SAND WERE IMPORTED TO BERM THE AREA PRIOR TO ATTEMPTING TO UPRIGHT THE TRUCK AND TRAILER. UNIQUE HEAVY HAUL WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE FUEL COMPARTMENTS SO ANY REMAINING PRODUCT COULD BE REMOVED BY DC CARRIERS' OFFLOAD TANKER. UNIQUE UP RIGHTED THE TANKER AND APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS SPILLED OUT OF THE TANKER INTO THE SAND THAT WAS PLACED AS A DIKE. ADDITIONAL SAND WAS BROUGHT IN AND WAS USED TO COVER THE GASOLINE IN THE BAR DITCH FOR VAPOR SUPPRESSION AND FOR THE SAFETY OF THE MOTORING PUBLIC. BOOMS WERE DEPLOYED AT THE CULVERT TO PREVENT ANY MORE GASOLINE FROM CROSSING THE HIGHWAY. THE SPILL ON THE ROADWAY WAS WASHED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD USING MICROBLAZE. THE SCENE WAS SECURED AND CREWS DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.

column168: DRIVER HAD AUTHORIZATION TO UNLOAD SIGNED BY PLANT PERSONNEL. DRIVER THEN BEGINS AIR OFF-LOADING INTO THE CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK. APPROXIMATELY 15 MINUTES INTO OFF LOAD THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK BEGINS TO OVERFLOW INTO AN IMPERVIOUS CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA. DRIVER SHUTS DOWN UNLOAD. THEN GOES AND INFORMS PLANT PERSONNEL. PLANT PERSONNEL RESPOND. DRIVER WITH ASSISTANCE FROM PLANT DRAINS DISCHARGE HOSES INTO BUCKETS, AND DRIVER STORES THEM AWAY. SAFETY SPOKE WITH PLANT MANAGER CHRIS. CHRIS ESTIMATES 200 OR MORE GALLONS ARE IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. HE STATED THEY HAVE CALLED THEIR ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR OUT TO DEAN UP. THEY ALSO TREATED THE ACID WITH SODA ASH. CHRIS DOES NOT HOLD THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE. ALL SPILLAGE OCCURRED INSIDE OF CUSTOMERS FACILITY BEYOND THE CONTROL OF CTL. NO CTL FAILURES CONTRIBUTED TO THIS EVENT.
column169: PLANT OPERATORS SHOULD MONITOR THEIR EQUIPMENT WHEN A DRIVER IS UNLOADING

column168: ON FRIDAY, MAY 6, 2016, AN RSI DELIVERY DRIVER WAS SCHEDULED TO DELIVER CHEMICALS TO A CUSTOMER LOCATION OFF OF HWY 27 NORTH OF HECTOR. THE SHORTEST ROUTE TO THE CUSTOMER LOCATION(S) WAS DETERMINED USING GOOGLE MAPS WHICH DIRECTED THE DRIVER TO HWY 16 AND THEN SOUTH ON HWY 27. THE DRIVER HAD JUST REACHED A SERIES OF SPEED RESTRICTED CURVES  AND AT ~10:06 HE APPROACHED A PORTION OF THE ROAD THAT CURVED TO THE LEFT AND OVER-STEERED TO THE LEFT RESULTING IN THE VEHICLE CROSSING THE CENTER LINE, OVER-STEERED TO THE RIGHT, AND THEN STEERED AGAIN TO THE LEFT. THE VEHICLE’S SPEED AND TURN ANGLE SHIFTED THE VEHICLE’S CENTER OF GRAVITY TO THE RIGHT, CAUSING IT TO ROLL 90 DEGREES ONTO THE PASSENGER (RIGHT) SIDE. THE VEHICLE SLID ALONG THE ROADWAY AND ONTO THE SHOULDER, AND CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE, ORIENTED IN THE GENERAL DIRECTION OF TRAVEL. IN THE COURSE OF THE ROLL-OVER, THE CARGO, WHICH CONSISTED OF EIGHT (8) 330-GALLON INTERMODAL BULK CONTAINERS (IBCs) WAS RELEASED FROM THE BED OF VEHICLE WHERE IT HAD BEEN SECURED WITH LOAD STRAPS. SEVEN OF THE EIGHT CONTAINERS FAILED WHEN THEY STRUCK THE GROUND, RELEASING THE MAJORITY OF THEIR CONTENTS, PROBABLY WITHIN A SPAN OF 0-15MINUTES. SOME MATERIAL WAS FORCIBLY EJECTED FROM SOME OF THE TOTES AND SPLASHED ON A HILLSIDE ADJACENT TO THE ROLLOVER SITE. UPON IMPACT, THE REAR WINDOW OF THE VEHICLE SHATTERED, AND AS THE IBC’S RUPTURED, PRODUCT SPLASHED INTO THE DRIVER COMPARTMENT RESULTING IN CHEMICAL EXPOSURE TO THE DRIVER. FROM THE POINT OF IMPACT ON THE WEST SIDE OF HWY 27, THE RELEASE FOLLOWED A ROADWAY DRAINAGE DITCH SOUTH TO A CULVERT, WHICH DIRECTED THE CHEMICAL ACROSS THE ROAD TO THE EAST AND INTO THE OZARK NATIONAL FOREST.     (SEE ATTACHMENT A FOR REMAINDER OF ACCOUNT SUMMARIZING EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND HAZMAT/SPILL RESPONSE).
column169: AN INITIAL INVESTIGATION AND VEHICLE INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE FRONT BRAKES WERE SLIGHTLY OUT OF ADJUSTMENT; HOWEVER, THE REAR BRAKES WERE FULLY FUNCTIONAL AND SHOULD HAVE BEEN SUFFICIENT TO SLOW OR STOP THE VEHICLE IF PROPER SHIFTING/BRAKING TECHNIQUES WERE USED. GIVEN THE STEEP GRADES IN THE AREA, IT IS POSSIBLE THAT EXCESSIVE AND IMPROPER BRAKE USE WAS THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THE FAILURE. THIS SUGGESTS THAT DRIVING HABITS IN HILLY OR MOUNTAINOUS AREAS CHARACTERIZED BY STEEP GRADES, ESPECIALLY WHILE LOADED, MAY ALSO HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THIS INCIDENT. AN INTERNAL SAFETY ALERT WILL BE DISTRIBUTED WHICH DISCUSSES THE HAZARDS AND PROPER DRIVING TECHNIQUES SPECIFIC TO GRADIENT TERRAIN. THE PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION INTO THIS INCIDENT CONCLUDED THAT, ROUTE SELECTION PLAYED A CRITICAL ROLE. FOR THAT REASON, THIS ROUTE IS NO LONGER ALLOWED PER THE RSI JOURNEY MANAGEMENT PROGRAM. ADDITIONAL ROUTE VERIFICATION/DISCUSSION WILL OCCUR AT THE NEXT DISTRICT SAFETY MEETING TO IDENTIFY OTHER POTENTIALLY HAZARDOUS ROUTES AND DISCUSS ROUTE VERIFICATION FOR NEW ROUTES AND DRIVERS. IN ADDITION, RSI EMPLOYEES WILL BE PROVIDED REFRESHER TRAINING TO ENSURE THE IDENTIFICATION OF ANY DEFICIENCIES THAT MAY IMPACT SAFE OPERATION OF A DELIVERY VEHICLE, AS WELL AS REINFORCING "STOP WORK" AUTHORITY TO ENSURE THAT THOSE DEFICIENCIES ARE CORRECTED PRIOR TO VEHICLE OPERATION/PLACEMENT IN SERVICE. FINALLY, RSI HAS RECOMMENDED THAT THE COMPANY OPEN A DIALOGUE WITH ITS CUSTOMER REGARDING DELIVERY FREQUENCY OPTIMIZATION. THIS WOULD IDEALLY LEAD TO A REDUCTION IN MILEAGE (AND TRANSPORTATION COST), REDUCE THE RISK OF TRANSPORTATION-RELATED INCIDENTS, AND IMPROVE OPERATING EFFICIENCY.

ADDITIONAL ROUTE VERIFICATION/DISCUSSION WILL OCCUR AT THE NEXT DISTRICT SAFETY MEETING TO IDENTIFY OTHER POTENTIALLY HAZARDOUS ROUTES AND DISCUSS ROUTE VERIFICATION FOR NEW ROUTES AND DRIVERS. IN ADDITION, RSI EMPLOYEES WILL BE PROVIDED REFRESHER TRAINING TO ENSURE THE IDENTIFICATION OF ANY DEFICIENCIES THAT MAY IMPACT SAFE OPERATION OF A DELIVERY VEHICLE, AS WELL AS REINFORCING "STOP WORK" AUTHORITY TO ENSURE THAT THOSE DEFICIENCIES ARE CORRECTED PRIOR TO VEHICLE OPERATION/PLACEMENT IN SERVICE. FINALLY, RSI HAS RECOMMENDED THAT THE COMPANY OPEN A DIALOGUE WITH ITS CUSTOMER REGARDING DELIVERY FREQUENCY OPTIMIZATION. THIS WOULD IDEALLY LEAD TO A REDUCTION IN MILEAGE (AND TRANSPORTATION COST), REDUCE THE RISK OF TRANSPORTATION-RELATED INCIDENTS, AND IMPROVE OPERATING EFFICIENCY.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: ON MAY 10, 2016, A 3-AXLE KENWORTH TANK TRUCK, OWNED BY AGRISOURCE- A DIVISION OF THE LYMAN GROUP, CARRYING APPROXIMATELY 3700 GALLONS OF AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE (AQUA AMMONIA, 24.5%) WAS TO BE DELIVERED TO A PORTABLE HOLDING TANK IN A RICE FIELD ADJACENT TO DANLEY LATERAL ROAD IN WILLIAMS, CALIFORNIA. THE DRIVER LEFT THE AGRISOURCE FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30AM TO DRIVE TO THE LOCATION. THE VEHICLE WAS DISCOVERED, AT APPROXIMATELY 11:10AM ON MAY 10, 2016, OVERTURNED IN A DITCH ON ITS ROOF WITH THE FRONT FORWARD CAB AREA PARTIALLY SUBMERGED IN WATER. THE TANK PORTION OF THE VEHICLE APPEARED INTACT. NO ONE OBSERVED THE INCIDENT. THE VEHICLE WAS PLACARDED AS CORROSIVE WITH PLACARD NUMBER 2672. THE INVESTIGATING OFFICER DETERMINED THAT AS THE DRIVER ENTERED INTO A RIGHT TURN ONTO A PRIVATE DIRT ROAD, TO HEAD NORTH, THE RIGHT SIDE TIRES LEFT THE EAST ROAD EDGE AND BEGAN TO TRAVEL DOWN THE DIRT EMBANKMENT AND THEN ROLLED OVER.     FOLLOWING THE COLLISION, APPROXIMATELY 3134 GALLONS OF AQUA AMMONIA WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK. IT WAS NOT POSSIBLE TO DETERMINE HOW LONG IT TOOK THE AQUA AMMONIA TO LEAK OUT OF THE TANK. COLUSA COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE WHERE THEY COORDINATED THE CLEANUP OF THE AQUA AMMONIA IN CONDUCTION WITH AGRISOURCE. THE YUBA-SUTTER HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SCENE TO ASSIST. THE CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR'S OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES (OES) WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT IMMEDIATELY AFTER IT WAS DISCOVERED. THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE ALSO ON SCENE: CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL, COLUSA COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT, MAXWELL FIRE DEPARTMENT, COLUSA COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES, CALIFORNIA STATE DEPARTMENT OF FISH AND WILDLIFE, GLENN COLUSA IRRIGATION DISTRICT, ENLOE EMS, AND WILLIAMS FIRE DEPARTMENT. AGRISOURCE AND THE LYMAN GROUP, INC. EMPLOYEES ALSO WERE ON SCENE AFTER THE INCIDENT.     THE 3" CAM LEVER COUPLER DUST CAP CAME OFF OF THE VENT OPENING ON THE TOP OF THE TANK, TOWARDS THE REAR OF THE TANK, DURING IMPACT AND THE AQUA AMMONIA WAS RELEASED FROM THE OPENING.     A COFFERDAM WAS PLACED IN THE DITCH, WHICH PREVENTED DITCH WATER FROM MOVING SOUTHWARD TOWARDS LURLINE CREEK. THE VEHICLE WAS TURNED UPRIGHT AND THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE TANK, APPROXIMATELY 584 GALLONS OF AQUA AMMONIA, WAS PUMPED INTO ANOTHER TANK TRUCK AND RETURNED TO THE AGRISOURCE FACILITY.     WATER WAS PUMPED INTO THE DITCH AND THEN PUMPED OUT OF THE DITCH ONTO NEIGHBORING FARMLAND, WITH PERMISSION FROM THE OWNER. THIS WAS DONE UNTIL THE PH OF THE WATER IN THE DITCH BECAME 7.0 GLENN COLUSA IRRIGATION DISTRICT, COLUSA COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (LOCAL CUPA), AND CALIFORNIA DEPARTMENT OF FISH AND WILDLIFE APPROVED THE REMOVAL OF THE COFFERDAM ON MAY 17, 2016.

column168: THIS TRUCK HAD A DRIVECAM MONITORING UNIT IN IT WHICH AFFIRMS THE BELOW:    WHILE TRANSPORTING LIQUID PROPANE TO DELIVER THE RESIDENTIAL CUSTOMERS OUR DRIVER APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION AT AN UNSAFE SPEED.     WHILE TRYING TO NAVIGATE THROUGH THE TURN AT AN UNSAFE RATE OF SPEED THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER INTO PRIVATE LAWN, WITH THE TRUCK RESTING ON ITS SIDE.     THE FORCE EXERTED ON THE CARGO PIPING SYSTEM DURING THE VIOLENT ROLLOVER CAUSED A CRACK IN THE LIQUID PIPE THAT RUNS TO THE CARGO DELIVERY HOSE REEL. THE CRACK WAS SUBSTANTIAL ENOUGH TO ALLOW LIQUID PROPANE TO RELEASE BUT NOT AT A RATE THAT ACTIVATED THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE. APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF PROPANE EVAPORATED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE DIESEL FUEL AND ENGINE OILS LEAKED INTO THE LAWN OF THE HOMEOWNER. THIS WAS REMEDIATED BY A PROFESSIONAL RESPONSE COMPANY AND THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE STATE OF PA.     THE DRIVER WAS INJURED AND TREATED/RELEASED AT THE EMERGENCY ROOM. THERE NO OTHER INJURIES OR FATALITIES.
column169: PACKAGING AND MATERIALS HELD UP WELL CONSIDERING THE FORCE EXERTED BY THE TRUCK ROLLING AT SUCH A HIGH RATE OF SPEED. THE EMPLOYEE WAS RELEASED FROM EMPLOYMENT FROM AMERIGAS PROPANE AS A RESULT OF HIS ACTIONS THAT LED TO THE ROLLOVER.
